Helminthoglypta umbilicata form cuestana


This is a very unusual form of H. umbilicata with it's very small dimensions, extremely flat spire and wholly open umbilicus. Dead shells observed along the hillside next to the ocean. No living snails were observed. 

I didn't observe any typical sized or high spired forms of H. umbilicata at this site. I'm unsure about the reproductive anatomy of this form but based on the consistency of this forms shell with it's extremely dwarfed size, flat spire and wide umbilicus I would think they would deserve a sub-species ranking.

description: As I was retracing my steps through the grassy hills, I saw a shine on the side of the trail that I figured for a metallic bag or some other piece of reflective trash, but as I got closer it turned out to be a nightjar!  Apparently the Common Poorwill is the most likely candidate.  When I was growing up, Common Nighthawks would join the early evening flocks of swallows in my neighborhood as they made a feast of summertime bugs, but I'd never seen a nightjar in CA before.  This guy was sitting on the trail, sort of a small, pigeon-sized black blob with reflective eyes and a small, sharp beak.  Despite having the wrong lens on, I raised my camera, but when my eye met the viewfinder, there was nothing there.  It had taken off soundlessly, ghostlike, and for a moment I questioned my sanity.

description: We found this poor little guy dead on the road.  Only one little button!

Continuing my self-education in flash photography, today I learned that a diffuser might be more important for larger, darker subjects.  My flash pics from today have also made me realize how important natural light to the mnemonic aspect of photography.  This could have been taken anywhere, at any time.  The rich, amber late afternoon light that falls on Mt. Diablo is all gone.
Tarantulas are back on Mt. D!
This egg-yolk jelly was enormous.  The bell was easily 2-3 ft in diameter, if not more.

I really wanted to get a quality shot of one of these since there don't seem to be any CC'd ones on Flickr yet, but ... I got distracted by the Dirona albolineata right next to it. Stupid show-stealing nudibranchs...

Brenna pointed this out, and while she was taking pics, I spotted an elbow crab right next door, which I had been hoping to photograph on this dive.  Sadly, she was done after I'd only taken a few pics of the crab, so I ended up with this reasonable slug shot and no good crab shot.  Doh.
Found two large (2-3 cm) Cuthona divae with many egg ribbons. Might be my first Cuthona spotted while diving, but given their size, it might not count.
Monastery is real, real nice.  Lots to see.
I noticed this guitarfish in about 20 ft of water as we were swimming back from our dive at Monastery. Brenna had air, so she went down for a closer look, and took a sweet picture.
